# <i>We go to a dance on a Saturday night</i>

45:16.640 --> 45:18.312
# <i>All alone I can hold her tight</i>

45:18.400 --> 45:20.994
# <i>But she lives on the 20th floor</i>
<i>up town</i>

45:21.080 --> 45:23.071
# <i>The elevator's broken down</i>

45:23.160 --> 45:25.549
# <i>So I walk one, two flight,</i>
<i>three flight, four</i>

45:25.640 --> 45:27.835
# <i>Five, six, seven flight,</i>
<i>eight flight more</i>

45:27.920 --> 45:30.036
# <i>Up on the 12th, I'm starting to drag</i>

45:30.120 --> 45:31.917
# <i>On the 15th floor, I'm ready to sag</i>

45:32.000 --> 45:35.197
# <i>When I get to the top,</i>
<i>I'm too tired to rock</i>

45:40.600 --> 45:43.672
- How old are you?
- 15.

45:43.760 --> 45:45.671
- <i>(John)</i> When?
- Last month.

45:46.840 --> 45:49.638
- I can do Little Richard as well.
- Sorry. Tick-tock.

45:49.720 --> 45:52.280
Nice to meet you
but we've got to rehearse.

45:52.960 --> 45:56.157
- Well, I've got to get off anyway...
- <i>(John)</i> Ta-ta, then.

45:56.240 --> 45:57.639
Alright.

46:03.640 --> 46:06.200
I'd rather him in our band
than anyone else's.

46:09.000 --> 46:10.991
<i>(doorbell rings)</i>

46:17.240 --> 46:19.310
John, your little friend is here.

46:19.400 --> 46:21.595
- <i>(strums guitar)</i>
- It goes A.

46:22.760 --> 46:24.671
But you start on D.

46:26.760 --> 46:28.796
<i>(tuts)</i> Bollocks! Hang on a sec.

46:30.240 --> 46:32.037
Keep going.

46:37.120 --> 46:40.476
- It's my Buddy Holly look.
- Good.

46:42.200 --> 46:44.555
- D.
- Right, yeah, D.

46:45.600 --> 46:48.831
So from D, it goes to E minor.

46:49.840 --> 46:52.912
No, B minor, that's a banjo chord.

46:54.240 --> 46:57.869
- <i>(John)</i> So B minor, it's...
- <i>(Paul)</i> Yeah, yeah, that's it.

46:58.880 --> 47:00.598
To G.

47:00.680 --> 47:02.796
G.

47:02.880 --> 47:04.472
To A.

47:05.600 --> 47:07.591
And then it just starts again.

47:08.920 --> 47:11.957
B minor to G.

47:13.600 --> 47:16.194
# <i>Blue moon</i>

47:18.080 --> 47:22.392
# <i>You saw me standing alone</i>

47:24.200 --> 47:28.193
# <i>Without a dream in my heart</i>

47:30.200 --> 47:33.590
# <i>Without a love of my own</i>

47:33.680 --> 47:36.274
<i>(thumping)</i>

47:42.400 --> 47:45.312
That's much better acoustically. Thanks.

47:47.000 --> 47:50.390
So, Mummy's cool about baby Paul
wanting to be Elvis?

47:51.280 --> 47:54.238
- She would have loved it.
- Bollocks!

47:55.040 --> 47:58.237
- She's not around any more.
- What?

47:59.000 --> 48:02.959
Well, she...
She sort of died last year.

48:06.840 --> 48:10.879
You know, if we're going to do this,
we should write our own stuff.

48:10.960 --> 48:13.758
Then you don't get stiffed
by record companies.

48:15.000 --> 48:16.718
I write stuff.

48:17.600 --> 48:20.990
Not songs, more poetry...
you know, stories.

48:21.080 --> 48:22.798
Add a tune and you've got a song.

48:22.880 --> 48:25.599
- Have you written any?
- A couple.

48:26.200 --> 48:28.270
How do you know so much?

48:28.360 --> 48:30.920
You don't seem like
the rock'n'roll kind of guy.

48:31.000 --> 48:34.788
You mean I don't go round smashing
things up and acting like a dick?

48:34.880 --> 48:35.915
Yeah.

48:36.000 --> 48:38.833
No. It's the music.

48:38.920 --> 48:41.354
That's it, it's just music. Simple.

48:55.880 --> 48:57.871
<i>(rock'n'roll music)</i>

49:56.480 --> 49:57.469
Where is it?

50:00.200 --> 50:04.239
- Mimi, where's my guitar?
- <i>(Mimi)</i> I've had your report.

50:04.320 --> 50:06.311
You promised me hard work.

50:06.400 --> 50:10.552
Lie and cheat all you want with others.
Do so with me and expect consequences!

50:11.600 --> 50:14.751
- Where is it?
- I've sold it.

50:15.880 --> 50:17.757
- You can't.
- I can and I have.

50:17.840 --> 50:20.957
- But we've got gigs.
- Oh, what a shame.

50:23.200 --> 50:24.599
Oh, boo-hoo!

50:24.680 --> 50:26.875
- But it's my group.
- Grow up, John.

50:26.960 --> 50:30.032
- Stop behaving like a child.
- Well, fuck off, Mimi.

50:30.120 --> 50:32.873
- What did you say?
- I said fuck off!

50:41.160 --> 50:43.071
# <i>I'm leaving town, baby</i>

50:43.160 --> 50:45.276
# <i>I'm leaving town for sure</i>

50:45.360 --> 50:49.069
# <i>Well, then, you won't be bothered</i>
<i>with me hanging round your door</i>

50:49.160 --> 50:50.798
# <i>Well, that's alright</i>

50:51.480 --> 50:53.471
# <i>That's alright</i>

50:53.560 --> 50:55.994
# <i>That's alright now, mama</i>

50:56.560 --> 50:59.154
# <i>Anyway you do</i>

51:00.000 --> 51:01.149
I need five quid.

51:01.240 --> 51:02.832
# <i>Dee, dee, de-de, dee</i>

51:02.920 --> 51:04.638
# <i>Do, do, de-de, dee</i>

51:05.320 --> 51:07.276
# <i>Dee, dee, de-de, dee</i>

51:07.360 --> 51:08.952
# <i>Dee-da, dee-da, dee</i>

51:09.040 --> 51:13.113
# <i>Easy loving, that's alright</i>

51:13.200 --> 51:18.399
So I got it back.
Yeah, Mum bought it for me.

51:22.400 --> 51:24.391
<i>(all cheer)</i>

51:31.600 --> 51:33.795
- Thanks, guys.
- Thank you.

51:36.360 --> 51:39.670
Next, the Scouse Duane Eddy
will play <i>Moving and Grooving.</i>

51:39.760 --> 51:41.990
I present to you Mr Paul McCharmly.

51:42.080 --> 51:44.071
- <i>(audience laughs)</i>
- Ta.

51:44.960 --> 51:48.157
- Thanks, John. Kind words.
- I didn't mean them.

51:48.240 --> 51:49.559
<i>(Julia laughs)</i>

51:51.480 --> 51:53.516
<i>(plays rock'n'roll)</i>

51:58.440 --> 51:59.873
Whoo!

52:26.800 --> 52:29.109
<i>(Paul) This is George.</i>
<i>He's a mate of mine.</i>

52:29.200 --> 52:33.239
- He should be in the group.
- He should be in bed.

52:33.320 --> 52:37.393
- No, I've been to bed. Couldn't sleep.
- Go on, George, show them.

52:38.000 --> 52:39.877
What? Magic tricks?

52:39.960 --> 52:42.394
No, I've left my top hat at home.

52:56.200 --> 52:58.589
<i>(plays mid-paced rock'n'roll)</i>

53:06.480 --> 53:08.277
<i>(song continues)</i>

53:51.200 --> 53:53.509
<i>(all cheer)</i>

53:55.240 --> 53:57.276
<i>(whoops)</i>

53:57.360 --> 53:59.191
Abracadabra eh, John?

54:05.160 --> 54:07.469
<i>(people chatter)</i>

54:09.560 --> 54:11.710
<i>(woman)</i> Gorgeous, isn't he?

54:15.560 --> 54:20.111
<i>(Julia)</i> I need to calm down now.
I'm embarrassing myself.

54:20.600 --> 54:22.795
- That was brilliant.
- Wasn't bad, was it?

54:22.880 --> 54:23.915
It was so good.

54:30.000 --> 54:32.798
We need to celebrate... everything.

54:33.720 --> 54:38.350
It's John's birthday soon so let's have
a party, at mine, Saturday. OK?

54:38.440 --> 54:41.796
- Can we get boozed up?
- Only if I can.

54:41.880 --> 54:45.998
- What about birds, Mrs Lennon?
- Let's just keep them in their cages.

54:47.600 --> 54:49.795
What do you reckon then, Johnny boy?

54:50.240 --> 54:54.518
- I think... I need a piss.
- <i>(boys laugh)</i>

55:02.240 --> 55:04.231
Who has got a light for a lady?

55:06.160 --> 55:08.151
<i>(toilet flushes)</i>

55:09.160 --> 55:11.151
Have you got a ticket?

55:12.800 --> 55:16.429
If you don't want her hanging
around the band, do something about it.

55:21.600 --> 55:23.397
It's my fucking band.

55:28.440 --> 55:30.590
John, the driver's not stopping.

55:33.280 --> 55:35.999
Thanks for that. Give us a ciggie.

55:37.960 --> 55:40.918
<i>(classical music plays softly)</i>

55:44.800 --> 55:47.678
Excuse me. That's very cosy.

55:53.440 --> 55:55.431
<i>(door shuts)</i>

56:00.600 --> 56:03.353
<i>(Pete)</i>
He said it's the police or the navy.

56:03.440 --> 56:05.749
My old man's giving me no other choice.

56:08.600 --> 56:12.195
Imagine me in a copper's uniform,
nicking people.

56:13.600 --> 56:15.591
Nicking you.

56:20.200 --> 56:22.395
I sometimes wish I had tits, you know?

56:23.560 --> 56:27.075
Not in a weird way,
just to have a little mess around with.

56:31.200 --> 56:33.316
- Hey, Winston?
- What?

56:33.400 --> 56:35.277
- This party.
- Yeah.

56:35.360 --> 56:36.952
We don't have to go.

56:37.840 --> 56:40.638
# <i>You ain't nothing but a hound dog</i>

56:42.000 --> 56:43.991
# <i>Been snooping round my door</i>

56:45.080 --> 56:47.674
# <i>You ain't nothing but a hound dog</i>

56:48.280 --> 56:50.919
# <i>Been snooping round my door</i>

56:51.000 --> 56:53.992
- # <i>You can wag your tail</i>
- <i>(boy)</i> Alright, John?

56:54.440 --> 56:56.908
# <i>But I ain't gonna feed you no more</i>

56:57.000 --> 56:58.991
Hi, John. How's it going, mate?

57:00.000 --> 57:02.673
<i>(Paul)</i> # <i>Love me true</i>

57:02.760 --> 57:06.639
# <i>All my dreams fulfil</i>

57:09.200 --> 57:14.991
# <i>For my darling, I love you</i>

57:15.800 --> 57:20.999
# <i>And I always will</i>

57:22.640 --> 57:24.995
That was for her, wasn't it? Your mum.

57:26.880 --> 57:31.032
It was awful. Taken away from you...
It's not fair.

57:32.200 --> 57:34.350
She had cancer.

57:35.040 --> 57:36.792
What's your excuse?

57:46.040 --> 57:48.076
Nice.

57:48.160 --> 57:51.391
# <i>You wag your tail</i>

57:51.480 --> 57:54.597
# <i>But I ain't gonna feed you no more</i>

57:55.840 --> 57:58.638
<i>(barking on record)</i>

58:01.840 --> 58:04.479
<i>(people chatter)</i>

58:04.560 --> 58:06.357
<i>("My Son John" by David Whitfield)</i>

58:08.480 --> 58:11.756
# <i>When a man has a son</i>

58:11.840 --> 58:14.752
# <i>Like my son John</i>

58:14.840 --> 58:17.912
- <i>(cheering)</i>
- # <i>He's a man who can smile</i>

58:18.000 --> 58:19.558
# <i>When he talks</i>

58:21.000 --> 58:24.356
# <i>And his eyes have a sparkle</i>

58:24.440 --> 58:27.000
<i>(all cheer)</i>

58:27.080 --> 58:31.949
Can someone turn that bloody record off
before I start crying... in pain?

58:32.040 --> 58:34.759
- <i>(all laugh)</i>
- <i>(boy)</i> Give us a few words, Johnny boy.

58:34.840 --> 58:38.310
Cock, balls, fuck.

58:38.400 --> 58:41.597
- <i>(John)</i> Is that allowed?
- <i>(all)</i> Speech! Speech!

58:42.520 --> 58:45.796
<i>(John)</i> Well, ta, for turning up.
You're very special to me...

58:45.880 --> 58:48.952
<i>(posh accent)</i>
...in that I hate you all equally.

58:49.040 --> 58:54.319
- <i>(all laugh)</i>
- Apart from you, Mum, obviously.

58:54.400 --> 58:56.391
Thanks for all this.

58:56.480 --> 58:58.835
Well, big clap, folks,
you know, for Julia.

58:58.920 --> 59:00.353
<i>(all cheer)</i>

59:01.840 --> 59:04.229
And my band. What can I say?

59:05.160 --> 59:09.278
You really are there for me. Never
on time, usually looking like shite,

59:09.360 --> 59:11.920
but, nevertheless,
you're there or thereabouts.

59:12.000 --> 59:13.831
Speak for yourself, eh, Lennon!

59:13.920 --> 59:17.310
- So, where are we going, boys?
- To the toppity top, Johnny.

59:17.400 --> 59:21.188
That's right. <i>(posh accent)</i>
To the toppity of one's topness.

59:21.280 --> 59:23.953
- Except the boy Shotton wants out.
- <i>(all groan)</i>

59:24.040 --> 59:27.635
I know. Apparently, washboard players
don't get enough chicks

59:27.720 --> 59:31.508
and he feels like a pansy
in his mum's sewing thimbles.

59:31.600 --> 59:34.353
- Come here, spunkhead.
- Ow!

59:34.440 --> 59:35.475
Ooh!

59:36.680 --> 59:38.636
Worth a few bob when we're famous.

59:38.720 --> 59:40.517
He's alright.

59:41.560 --> 59:45.872
- <i>(Pete)</i> For fuck's sake!
- <i>("Be-Bop-A-Lula" by Gene Vincent)</i>

59:45.960 --> 59:47.951
<i>(Julia laughs)</i>

59:58.200 --> 01:00:00.634
- Where are you going?
- I'm going for a ciggie.

01:00:00.720 --> 01:00:02.278
Have one here.

01:00:17.200 --> 01:00:21.591
I wonder if someone's up there on Mars,
having a quick cigarette like me.

01:00:21.680 --> 01:00:23.079
Where's Dad?

01:00:24.200 --> 01:00:27.670
They're called dads, right?
Most people I know have got one.

01:00:27.760 --> 01:00:31.355
- I don't think...
- Oh, don't you, Mum? Well, I do.

01:00:32.440 --> 01:00:34.829
Think, think, think. That's all I do.

01:00:36.880 --> 01:00:40.793
Where's Daddy, Mummy?
Alf, that's his name, right?

01:00:44.120 --> 01:00:46.793
- Where's fucking Alf?
- Please don't swear, John.

01:00:46.880 --> 01:00:48.552
Make you feel uncomfortable?

01:00:48.640 --> 01:00:52.428
Try being me for 17 years when everyone
asks why your auntie is your mum.

01:00:52.520 --> 01:00:54.795
Now, that's uncomfortable.

01:00:58.200 --> 01:01:00.509
Oh, here we go.

01:01:01.720 --> 01:01:04.473
Who turned the taps on?

01:01:04.560 --> 01:01:09.076
- Please don't be horrible to me, John.
- Oh! Me being horrible to you?

01:01:09.160 --> 01:01:12.948
Oh, I see. Horrible John,
naughty John, poor Julia.

01:01:13.040 --> 01:01:16.919
No, no. No walking away. I know
you're good at it, but not tonight.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:19.195
- Where is he?
- Oh!

01:01:21.400 --> 01:01:26.155
- New Zealand, maybe. I don't know.
- Not round the corner, like you?

01:01:28.200 --> 01:01:30.395
He was in the merchant navy.

01:01:30.480 --> 01:01:34.314
No letters, no money. He abandoned us.

01:01:34.400 --> 01:01:36.277
Then you abandoned me!

01:01:36.360 --> 01:01:39.079
It was a temporary thing. Mimi agreed.

01:01:39.160 --> 01:01:41.515
Temporary? I'm still living with her.

01:01:41.600 --> 01:01:45.388
- I always wanted you back.
- Oh, I believe you. Honest.

01:01:45.480 --> 01:01:47.948
She never gave you back.

01:01:48.040 --> 01:01:51.237
But surely I'm not Mimi's to give.

01:01:51.320 --> 01:01:53.197
You're my mum.

01:01:55.920 --> 01:01:58.753
She... She loves you so much.

01:01:59.360 --> 01:02:02.397
Yeah, more than you.

01:02:04.320 --> 01:02:07.676
<i>(girl)</i> Mummy? I'm tired now.

01:02:09.240 --> 01:02:13.358
- Are you sad again?
- Mummy's not sad. Look.

01:02:14.600 --> 01:02:16.795
I'm coming in now, honey.

01:02:16.880 --> 01:02:18.472
Go on.

01:02:23.520 --> 01:02:26.318
I do love you. Believe me.

01:02:26.400 --> 01:02:29.073
Believe me, I would love to.

01:02:29.960 --> 01:02:33.555
- John, where are you going?
- Away from you.

01:03:12.440 --> 01:03:15.034
- <i>(door shuts)</i>
- <i>(John)</i> Mimi.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:23.991
You said you'd be back.

01:03:24.840 --> 01:03:28.071
I think I'll just...
I've got some work to finish.

01:03:34.400 --> 01:03:36.470
It was meant to be a surprise.

01:03:42.880 --> 01:03:44.029
A Hoffner!

01:03:45.200 --> 01:03:46.553
Mimi.

01:03:47.600 --> 01:03:49.909
Ooh, you stink of alcohol.

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:52.195
Mum threw a party for me.

01:03:54.200 --> 01:03:55.792
Oh.

01:03:57.800 --> 01:03:59.995
That's a waste, isn't it?

01:04:05.200 --> 01:04:06.394
<i>(doorbell rings)</i>

01:04:06.480 --> 01:04:09.358
<i>(Mimi)</i>
Tell your friends the party's over.

01:04:17.200 --> 01:04:19.191
No, thanks.

01:04:20.800 --> 01:04:23.394
- We've got a gatecrasher.
- I need to talk to John.

01:04:23.480 --> 01:04:25.471
Oh, more talking? Wow!

01:04:25.560 --> 01:04:28.358
You see, me and Mum
have had a bit of a heart-to-heart.

01:04:28.440 --> 01:04:32.353
Yes, she told me things about...
Oh, what's his name...? Alf.

01:04:32.440 --> 01:04:35.716
Oh, and about you, funnily enough.
Yeah, she said you stole me.

01:04:35.800 --> 01:04:38.792
- What do you reckon, Mimi?
- I never said that.

01:04:38.880 --> 01:04:42.270
You said, quote, "She," as in you,
Mimi, "never gave you back."

01:04:42.360 --> 01:04:45.955
When I don't give things back,
I've got to admit, I'm usually stealing.

01:04:46.040 --> 01:04:48.918
What on earth have you
been telling him, Julia?

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:52.195
Did she say why I stole you?

01:04:52.280 --> 01:04:54.669
Well, there she is. Ask her yourself.

01:04:54.760 --> 01:04:58.116
Did she mention having another man's
child to deal with? A daughter?

01:04:58.200 --> 01:04:59.394
Mimi, please.

01:04:59.480 --> 01:05:03.075
<i>(Mimi)</i> Please what? Stop? Look at him.

01:05:03.160 --> 01:05:04.673
Do you think we can stop now?

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:11.192
Whose child?

01:05:11.920 --> 01:05:15.549
<i>(Mimi)</i> Go on, tell him, as you're
so keen for him to know the truth.

01:05:16.320 --> 01:05:18.356
What daughter?

01:05:22.920 --> 01:05:27.072
Your mother has always needed company.
Do you understand what I mean?

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:29.911
Rock'n'roll, eh, Mum?

01:05:32.640 --> 01:05:38.237
And she found it, with a young soldier
whilst your father was away at sea.

01:05:38.320 --> 01:05:40.675
You have another sister. Victoria.

01:05:44.720 --> 01:05:46.597
Where is she? Where?

01:05:46.680 --> 01:05:50.275
We don't know. Salvation Army took her.

01:05:54.400 --> 01:05:55.992
<i>(sobs)</i>

01:05:56.080 --> 01:05:57.877
<i>(Mimi)</i> Then, after that,

01:05:57.960 --> 01:06:02.238
your mother decides to shack up
with another fancy man, Bobby.

01:06:03.240 --> 01:06:05.515
Still married to your father,
I might add,

01:06:05.600 --> 01:06:09.036
and then bring you up as if that was
acceptable, as if that was normal.

01:06:10.040 --> 01:06:12.235
When your father came home
after the war,

01:06:12.320 --> 01:06:16.108
he wanted to try and save the marriage,
but she'd have none of it.

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:18.191
She told him to get lost.

01:06:20.360 --> 01:06:23.033
But Alf wasn't giving up that easily.
Was he, Julia?

01:06:23.120 --> 01:06:26.510
Hmm? Oh, feel free
to join the conversation.

01:06:28.400 --> 01:06:30.391
No, I didn't think she would.

01:06:35.400 --> 01:06:38.597
You were staying here with me
at Mendips

01:06:38.680 --> 01:06:40.875
when Alf turned up out of the blue.

01:06:42.480 --> 01:06:44.789
He said he wanted to take you
into Liverpool.

01:06:44.880 --> 01:06:48.714
I thought he was genuine but he took you
to Blackpool instead. He kidnapped you.

01:06:48.800 --> 01:06:51.553
Turned out he'd organised
a passage to New Zealand.

01:06:51.640 --> 01:06:55.030
Got himself a job out there.
Wanted to take you with him.

01:06:56.080 --> 01:06:58.958
We hadn't a clue where you were.
I was distraught!

01:06:59.480 --> 01:07:02.677
The Seaman's Mission had an address
for a relative in Blackpool

01:07:02.760 --> 01:07:04.796
so we went to find you,
to bring you back.

01:07:08.280 --> 01:07:12.159
